Name: automation
Description: GUI automation wrapper around pyautogui.
Version: 1.0

Overview:
This toolset exposes common mouse, keyboard, and screenshot actions. Every
command supports `return_screenshot` which, when true, captures and returns a
path to a screenshot after the action.
It also auto-registers wrappers for every pyautogui function as
`auto_<function_name>`, using generic args/kwargs.

Commands:
- auto_call
  Call any pyautogui function by name (covers all features).
  Parameters: func, args (array, optional), kwargs (object, optional), return_screenshot

- auto_<pyautogui_function>
  Auto-generated wrapper for each pyautogui function.
  Parameters: args (array, optional), kwargs (object, optional), return_screenshot

- auto_move_to
  Move mouse to absolute coordinates.
  Parameters: x, y, duration (optional), return_screenshot (optional)

- auto_move_rel
  Move mouse relative to current position.
  Parameters: x, y, duration (optional), return_screenshot (optional)

- auto_click
  Click mouse (optional coordinates).
  Parameters: x (optional), y (optional), clicks, interval, button, return_screenshot

- auto_double_click
  Double click mouse.
  Parameters: x (optional), y (optional), interval, button, return_screenshot

- auto_right_click
  Right click mouse.
  Parameters: x (optional), y (optional), return_screenshot

- auto_drag_to
  Drag mouse to absolute coordinates.
  Parameters: x, y, duration, button, return_screenshot

- auto_drag_rel
  Drag mouse relative to current position.
  Parameters: x, y, duration, button, return_screenshot

- auto_scroll
  Scroll the wheel.
  Parameters: clicks, x (optional), y (optional), return_screenshot

- auto_type
  Type text.
  Parameters: text, interval (optional), return_screenshot

- auto_press
  Press a key.
  Parameters: key, presses (optional), interval (optional), return_screenshot

- auto_hotkey
  Press a key combination.
  Parameters: keys (array), return_screenshot

- auto_key_down
  Hold a key.
  Parameters: key, return_screenshot

- auto_key_up
  Release a key.
  Parameters: key, return_screenshot

- auto_position
  Get current mouse position.
  Parameters: return_screenshot

- auto_screen_size
  Get screen size.
  Parameters: return_screenshot

- auto_screenshot
- auto_locate_on_screen
- auto_locate_all_on_screen
- auto_center
- auto_alert
- auto_confirm
- auto_prompt
- auto_set_pause
- auto_set_failsafe
- auto_wait_for_image
  Capture a screenshot.
  Parameters: path (optional), region (optional [left, top, width, height]), return_screenshot

Usage Examples:
- auto_call func="position" return_screenshot=true
- auto_call func="locateOnScreen" args=["needle.png"] kwargs={"confidence":0.8}
- auto_move_to x=200 y=300 return_screenshot=true
- auto_click x=200 y=300 clicks=2
- auto_hotkey keys=["ctrl","c"]
- auto_type text="Hello" interval=0.02 return_screenshot=true
- auto_screenshot

Behavior Notes:
- Screenshots are saved in a `screenshots` folder under the working directory.
- Coordinates are in screen pixels.

Dependencies:
- pyautogui
